{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "626c9b41",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Number of Circuits: Why it matters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a60c5392",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We demonstrate how combining several circuits in one job increases speed of execution & usage of QPU time. This will also shed some light on why the allowed number of circuits was recently increased"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3491f388",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Load modules, account and backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "\n",
    "#Hellinger Fidelity for comparing different count distributions\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "# For plotting\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use('ibmq-dark')\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format='retina'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "IBMQ.active_account()==None and IBMQ.load_account() \n",
    "\n",
    "provider = IBMQ.get_provider(group='dev-sys-software')\n",
    "backend = provider.backend.ibm_peekskill"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Explore maximum number of experiments (circuits)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us list all the attributes of `backend.configuration()` ..."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "dict_keys(['n_uchannels', 'u_channel_lo', 'meas_levels', 'qubit_lo_range', 'meas_lo_range', 'meas_kernels', 'discriminators', 'hamiltonian', 'rep_times', 'dt', 'dtm', 'channels', '_qubit_channel_map', '_channel_qubit_map', '_control_channels', 'acquisition_latency', 'conditional_latency', 'meas_map', '_data', 'backend_name', 'backend_version', 'n_qubits', 'basis_gates', 'gates', 'local', 'simulator', 'conditional', 'open_pulse', 'memory', 'max_shots', 'coupling_map', 'supported_instructions', 'dynamic_reprate_enabled', 'rep_delay_range', 'default_rep_delay', 'max_experiments', 'sample_name', 'n_registers', 'credits_required', 'online_date', 'description', 'processor_type', 'parametric_pulses'])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "backend.configuration().__dict__.keys()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "... to find that that the relevant attribute here is `max_experiments`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "300"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "backend.configuration().max_experiments"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fc88d19d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Alternatively using the new class of backends [`BackendV2`](https://qiskit.org/documentation/stubs/qiskit.providers.BackendV2.html), `max_experiments` is a direct attribute of this class. Access to backends using `BackendV2` is managed by qiskit-ibm-provider, which you may install by running \n",
    "```\n",
    "pip install qiskit-ibm-provider\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "4975cfe3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit_ibm_provider import IBMProvider\n",
    "provider2 = IBMProvider()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 71,
   "id": "fd163ede",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "version = 2 , maximum number of circuits = 300\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "backend2=provider2.backend.ibm_peekskill\n",
    "print(\"version =\",backend2.version,\", maximum number of circuits =\",backend2.max_experiments)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Timing of circuits in one job vs individual jobs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will run an exemplary circuit and compare how much time it takes to run\n",
    "- an individual circuit\n",
    "- a list of several circuits in one job\n",
    "- several jobs with an individual circuit each\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us use a GHZ-state-creating circuit as an example"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 485.729x264.88 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 30,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 236,
       "width": 407
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ = QuantumCircuit(4)\n",
    "circ.h(0)\n",
    "circ.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "circ.cx(1, 2)\n",
    "circ.cx(2, 3)\n",
    "circ.measure_all\n",
    "\n",
    "circ_transpiled = transpile(circ,backend)\n",
    "circ_transpiled.draw(idle_wires=False)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Individual circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We run the circuit individually and look at the time taken, provided by the job's `result` method (in seconds)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "single_job = backend.run(circ_transpiled)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "9.48"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "round(single_job.result().time_taken,2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### List of circuits within one job"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us see what happens when the same circuit is run 20 times, by passing a corresponding list to the backend to run"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "multiple_circuits_job = backend.run([circ_transpiled]*20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "86.3"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "round(multiple_circuits_job.result().time_taken,1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We find this is much faster than the run time of the individual circuit multiplied by the same number"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "189.5"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "round(single_job.result().time_taken*20,1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### List of jobs containing an individual circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We confirm the previous observation by actually running the same job 20 times and looking at the total time"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 53,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "multiple_jobs = [backend.run(circ_transpiled) for i in range(20)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Gathering & adding up the time taken for each job in our list"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "200.7"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "time_taken_multiple_jobs=[job.result().time_taken for job in multiple_jobs]\n",
    "\n",
    "round(sum(time_taken_multiple_jobs),1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 418,
       "width": 734
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "bars = ax.barh(['single job containing 20 circuits','single job duration x 20','20 jobs containing one circuit each'], \n",
    "[multiple_circuits_job.result().time_taken,single_job.result().time_taken*20,sum(time_taken_multiple_jobs)])\n",
    "ax.set_title('Methods of circuit bundling vs execution time')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Duration in seconds');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see indeed that the fastest way to run several circuits is to bundle them in a list of circuits within one job."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Looking at the \"Why\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So what is the reason that piling up circuits in one job is actually more effective?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One reason is the overhead that comes with each job. A job needs to be embedded in a whole infrastructure that allows for transmission of the data, compilation of instructions to microwave signals by the Room Temperature Electronics (RTE), communication in the internal IT infrastructure, idle times (rep_delay) between different circuits or shots and, the execution of the circuit on the quantum chip and the transmission of results. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Another reason is the way circuits are executed on the backend. In the example here, where the same circuit is executed several times with no difference in idle times, the circuits included in the job are actually executed by iterating over the circuits for **each shot**. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "```{figure} images/hw/circuits_shots_matrix1.png\n",
    "---\n",
    "name: colum-wise exec\n",
    "---\n",
    "Matrix of four circuits in a job showing the execution pattern over the circuits\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Iterating over shots for all circuits first, before looping over circuits, allows to reduce the overhead in transmitting the results from each circuit. \n",
    "We will look at further details of the execution of jobs on the hardware in a future post on ``rep_delay``."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
